Kindergarten was sure excited to check out books from the library cart today!
Elementary students will choose a book each week from the cart Ms. Ray will bring around. They must return their book to receive another one on their next library day as follows:
Monday - 2nd
Tuesday- 3rd
Wednesday- Kindergarten
Thursday - 4th
Friday - 1st
5th grade and up may email Ms. Ray a specific book they would like by looking up our selections in the library catalog.

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Meagan Yonker

Meagan Violet Yonker is the daughter of Nick and Stacy Yonker of Garden. During high school. Meagan participated in basketball, volleyball, soccer, golf, track, softball, cross country, Health Occupations of America, student forum, and Science Olympiad. Meagan served as captain of the basketball team, captain of the volleyball team, captain of the soccer team, and Class President. Outside of school Meagan enjoys kayaking, camping, running, hiking, and going for motorcycle rides. After graduation, Meagan plans on attending Bay College then transfer to NMU in the surgical tech program.

After graduation, Gary plans to attend Bay College and pursue welding and auto mechanic certificates while he continues to work in the field of excavating.

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Hailey Farley

Hailey Lynn Farley, is the daughter of Heather Guertin of Garden and Morgan Farley of Manistique. During high school, Hailey was involved in Robotics and Science Olympiad. Hailey was the secretary of her class. She also was on homecoming court three years in a row and during her Senior year she was crowned homecoming queen. Outside of school Hailey enjoys hunting, go for walks, write, spend time with her cousins, and lastly loves to take her dog swimming at the beach. After graduation, Hailey plans to attend Bay College and go into the healthcare field. After getting her degree in Nursing she will like to work in the Intensive Care Unit.

Plans are already in the works for summer of 2021. We hope to see you then. Stay safe, stay healthy.

Gary, Jeff, Shannon, Marcia, John, Alex

post_text: Thank you all again for the opportunity to deliver meals to our students. It is truly our pleasure, and we look forward to each Thursday. We miss it all...the smiles, the hugs, the giggles, the conversations, the excitement, the complaining, the learning, and the activity. Please stay in communication with us. We love hearing from all of you and will keep looking for you in the windows on Thursdays. Stay healthy and safe, Black Bears! Even though we are apart, you are not alone. We are in this together. For students whose families do not currently have a SNAP/Bridge card, one will be mailed as soon as this week with the first allotment for each eligible child loaded on it and with instructions on how to call and add a pin to the card. The new cards will not include the bridge picture and will be rather plain in appearance. They will likely be mailed to the oldest child in the household and will be preloaded with $193.80 per eligible child.

For students whose families already partake in the SNAP/Bridge Card program, the first additional P-EBT money allotment was loaded Friday onto your existing cards.
text:
Big Bay de Noc School participates in the Community Eligibility Program (CEP) for our food service. This status, combined with the Pandemic-EBT program means that all Big Bay de Noc Students grades K-12 should receive the P-EBT benefit.

For students whose families do not currently have a SNAP/Bridge card, one will be mailed as soon as this week with the first allotment for each eligible child loaded on it and with instructions on how to call and add a pin to the card. The new cards will not include the bridge picture and will be rather plain in appearance. They will likely be mailed to the oldest child in the household and will be preloaded with $193.80 per eligible child.

For students whose families already partake in the SNAP/Bridge Card program, the first additional P-EBT money allotment was loaded Friday onto your existing cards.

post_text:
This just in from Mrs. Novak!
I'm excited to report that many 5th graders learned math from our regular textbook today online using Google Hangouts or the telephone. And, it was very successful. I love seeing their faces. My students have worked hard over these past 3 weeks being home. From this day forward, they will learn from me via video and chatting on Google Hangouts. Also, they will email me and complete assignments via Google Classroom. Learning has not stopped in our 5th grade classroom. We have just moved it into the cloud! I've included a picture of my teacher workstation at home (with Garfield posters!!!) and screens of us learning. Stay safe and healthy!

post_text:
With Governor Whitmer's executive order changing school from face-to-face instruction to distance learning today, the remainder of the school year will look a bit different than what we are used to at Big Bay de Noc School. Student health and safety is always our primary concern. We have been working to develop creative ways to deliver quality learning experiences for the remainder of the year and look forward learning and growing with all of you as we work together through these unusual circumstances.

Our Big Bay de Noc Teachers worked hard this week to collect the materials your children need to complete their work moving forward. We will continue this process of sending materials homeâ€¦

A message from OSF Hospital:
>>>>>>> master

We are recommending patients go to www.osfhealthcare.org to utilize our chatbot Clare, a digital assistant capable of educating and triaging people who are concerned about COVID-19.

Additionally, community members can use OSF COVID Companion, which is a free text messaging tool that provides guidance about COVID-19. The text messaging program links users with critical recommendations from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services. To subscribe, users can text OSF to 67634. People also have a third digital option, which is to call the triage line directly at (833) OSF-KNOW.

Please consider sharing our Facebook posts about Clare and OSF COVID Companion, as they have proved to be very helpful. Most importantly, these screening services limit the number of people unnecessarily entering our facilities during this time.

Food Delivery Update:
>>>>>>> master
Our buses will be delivering meals door-to-door tomorrow, Tuesday, March 17th for our Big Bay de Noc Students.

The buses will depart the school at 9:00am and deliver to each home on the routes. If you donâ€™t normally ride the bus or get on at a pick-up location, we will be bringing the delivery to your home. Please plan for delivery between 9:00am and noon. Staff members will be assisting drivers and running food to the doors for drop-off. This will be a three-day meal delivery and will include lunch and breakfast options for each day for each child.

The next planned delivery will be Friday, March 20th during the same 9:00am-noon timeframe and will include meals for Friday and the upcoming week.

Additionally, we are asking our secondary students to log into their school email accounts Wednesday morning for communications from teachers. Elementary teachers will be sending more work home periodically during our food delivery routes.

Stay healthy, Black Bears!

post_text:
The COVID-19 Pandemic and subsequent school closures are an unprecedented situation for our communities. The situation remains extremely fluid as new information is becoming available each day. As of now, Big Bay de Noc School will be closed for any and all public and student events and use until Monday, April 6, 2020. The MHSAA is prohibiting athletic practices, scrimmages, and competitions/games/meets. We will be communicating via our Facebook page and website any updates as this situation progresses.

During the next three weeks, the school will be coordinating meal delivery for students. More specific information regarding this service will be released early next week.

It brings us great sadness to inform everyone that we will not be holding our 2020 Escanaba District Competition that was supposed to be held this weekend. We would like to thank everyone that has put in so much hard work and dedication to this event, and we hope to continue next season.

March 11, 2020
Due to the current and potential threat of the COVID-19 (Coronavirus) in our state and in accordance with public health recommendations, FIRST in Michigan has decided that, effective immediately, the upcoming FIRST in Michigan FRC District Events in our state will be postponed until further notice. At this time, FLL and FTC spring season events, scheduled for May, will be held as planned.

Thisâ€¦

post_text: The Peninsula Federal Credit Union gave a banking presentation to the 3rd through 5th graders today. They were taught about savings accounts, checking accounts, debit cards, credit cards, budgets, and paychecks. The bankers had the students pick out things they wanted but they only had so much money so they needed to make sacrifices in order to have what they truly wanted. Then they were shown how to write a check, how to pay bills, and the importance of saving money as soon as possible! Along with the history of money and how to spot fake money. Thank you to PFCU for coming to teach such valuable lessons!

column20: The Peninsula Federal Credit Union gave a banking presentation to the 3rd through 5th graders today. They were taught about savings accounts, checking accounts, debit cards, credit cards, budgets, and paychecks. The bankers had the students pick out things they wanted but they only had so much money so they needed to make sacrifices in order to have what they truly wanted. Then they were shown how to write a check, how to pay bills, and the importance of saving money as soon as possible! Along with the history of money and how to spot fake money. Thank you to PFCU for coming to teach such valuable lessons!

post_text: Piper Jones is this weekâ€™s Student of the Week for Big Bay de Noc School. Piper is the daughter of Tracy and Sarah Jones. As a freshman, Piper has shown to be successful in both academics and athletics. Piper is always participating in classroom discussions. She does her work on time and is willing to help other classmates when needed. Piper is a well rounded individual with high academic marks and she is involved in volleyball, soccer, and basketball. She is also involved in robotics and was on the Quiz Bowl team. Piper is a joy to have in class and a breath of fresh air! Piper Jones represents what Black Bear pride is all about!

post_text:
Our eighth grade students will visit the Delta-Schoolcraft Intermediate School (DSISD) and Bay College this Friday February 28th. They will attend the 8th Grade Career Exploration program, hosted by Delta County College Access Network (DCCAN), to hear about opportunities that will be provided during high school.
DCCAN hosts various programs to increase the percentage of students going to college in Michigan. It is a local branch of the Michigan College Access Network, which is working toward raising the percentage of students attending college in Michigan by the year 2025. Programs provided by DCCAN include 5th Grade Fridays, 8th Grade Career Exploration and Junior and Senior Career Fairs.

post_text: Ms. Pederson and the Third Grade worked on the writing process before Thanksgiving break. They wrote rough drafts, edited with a peer, edited with a teacher, and wrote the final draft of a short essay. Their goal was to persuade the reader to not eat turkey this Thanksgiving. The class sent their story in to StudentTreasures. In which they turned their writing into a published book and today was the day that book came! The students were all excited to read them and look through the books.

Congratulating this weeks Student of the Week:
Carter Frazer! Both inside and outside of the classroom Carter strives to excel at the task at hand. The son of Daniel and Tasha Frazer, Carter pushes himself to be his very best as a student. This drive continues on the court as a member of the Junior High Basketball team. Carterâ€™s academic prowess is also a key factor in his participation in both the Middle School Quiz Bowl Team and Junior High Science Olympiad. When not working on his academics he enjoys playing basketball. He also enjoys spending time with his cousins and other family. Carter has mastered the technique of balancing successful hard-work and relaxation and fun with great ability. It is very rare to come across Carter without a smile on his face and an immediate goal in mind which will serve him well in his future.
